{"id":"1508.03913","submitter":"Hubert Lacoin","authors":"Jonathan Hermon, Hubert Lacoin and Yuval Peres","title":"Total Variation and Separation Cutoffs are not equivalent and neither\n  one implies the other","comments":"37 pages, 9 figures. Details added for some proofs and minor\n  corrections","journal-ref":"Electronic Journal of Probability 21 (2016), Paper No. 44,","doi":"10.1214/16-EJP4687","report-no":"MR3530321","categories":"math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The cutoff phenomenon describes the case when an abrupt transition occurs in\nthe convergence of a Markov chain to its equilibrium measure. There are various\nmetrics which can be used to measure the distance to equilibrium, each of which\ncorresponding to a different notion of cutoff. The most commonly used are the\ntotal-variation and the separation distances. In this note we prove that the\ncutoff for these two distances are not equivalent by constructing several\ncounterexamples which display cutoff in total-variation but not in separation\nand with the opposite behavior, including lazy simple random walk on a sequence\nof uniformly bounded degree expander graphs. These examples give a negative\nanswer to a question of Ding, Lubetzky and Peres.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 17 Aug 2015 02:36:13 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 18 Dec 2015 09:07:44 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 22 Apr 2016 22:04:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-01-29"}
